@kvelr1851- nice of you to educate me on how my country works.  
Employers are not obligated to pay a significant portion of health insurance, nor are the coverage levels specified.  For many businesses, it is common that only a basic plan is offered and the employee will pay the majority of premiums.  Dont expect coverage for mental health or contraception, and even basic medical tests may be denied by the insurance company as unnecessary.  Expect to have significant co-pays. Dental and vision care are separate. I am fortunate that I work for the US division of a European company so I have good coverage and still have a $6000 deductible, on top of paying monthly premiums for a family of 3 which total thousands of dollars per year.  And we wont even start on drug prices.  Also, if youre unemployed, since you have no employer to offer insurance, what you can get on the open market is either expensive, limited, or both.

This is completely unrelated to the current administration - the US healthcare system has been broken for many years.

